      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <p><pb n="2r"/><!--
I number the pages of these Belora plates as they would have stood in a three-plate document, though I restart line numbers in each.
--><lb n="1"/>satyārjjava-kāruṇya-śauryya-vikkrama-naya-vinaya-māhātmya-śrīma<sic>tv</sic>a-dhīma<supplied reason="omitted">ttva</supplied>-pātragata-bhaktitva-
<lb n="2"/>dharmma-vijayitva-ma<unclear>no</unclear>-nairmmalyādi-guṇai<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> samupetasya <space/> varṣaśatam-abhivarddhamāna-kośa-da<lb break="no" n="3"/>ṇḍa-sādhana-sa<unclear>ntā</unclear>na-<space type="binding-hole"/>putra-paut<choice>
            <sic>r̥</sic>
            <corr>ri</corr>
          </choice>ṇaḥ yudhiṣ<choice>
            <sic>v</sic>
            <corr>ṭh</corr>
          </choice>ira-vr̥tte<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> vāk<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice>ṭakānām-mahārāja-śrī-p<sic>ri</sic>thīvī<choice>
            <sic>s</sic>
            <corr>ṣ</corr>
          </choice>e<lb break="no" n="4"/><choice>
            <sic>n</sic>
            <corr>ṇ</corr>
          </choice>asya s<choice>
            <sic>u</sic>
            <corr>ū</corr>
          </choice>nor bhagavataś-cakkrapāṇeḫ prasād-opārj<unclear>j</unclear>ita-śrī-samudayasya<surplus>|</surplus> mahārāja-śrī-rudrasena<lb break="no" n="5"/>sya s<choice>
            <sic>u</sic>
            <corr>ū</corr>
          </choice>nor mmahārājādhirāja-śrī-devagupta-sutāyām prabhāvat<sic>i</sic>guptāyām utpannasya śambhoḫ pra<lb break="no" n="6"/>sāda-dhr̥t<choice>
            <sic>i</sic>
            <corr>a</corr>
          </choice>-kārtta-yugasya vākāṭakānām parama-māheśvara-mahārāja-śrī-pravarasenasya<!--
The superfluous punctuation in l4 is probably a very short horizontal; not very clear in the rubbing.
--><!--
Instead of mmahārājādhirāja in l5, Mirashi only prints mmahārāja in CII, but his text is correct in EI24.
--><pb n="2v"/><lb n="7"/>vacanā<unclear>T|</unclear>
</p>
        <p>ś<choice>
            <sic>e</sic>
            <corr>ai</corr>
          </choice>lapura-mārge Asi-bhukti-mahallalāṭa-grām<choice>
            <sic>e</sic>
            <corr>a</corr>
          </choice>ḥ pravareśvara-ṣadviśaka-vāṭa<lb break="no" n="8"/>ka-vastavyāya<surplus>|</surplus> tait<unclear>t</unclear>irīyāya<surplus>|</surplus> kāśyapa-sagotra-śūryyasvāmine dattaḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> yato smat-sa<choice>
            <sic>t</sic>
            <corr>n</corr>
          </choice>takāḥ sarvvād<supplied reason="omitted">dh</supplied>ya<lb break="no" n="9"/>kṣa-niy<choice>
            <sic>ā</sic>
            <corr>o</corr>
          </choice>ga-niyuktāḥ <space type="binding-hole"/>ājñā-saṁcāri-kula-putrādhikr̥tā bhaṭāś chāt<unclear>t</unclear>rāś ca viśruta-pūrvvayājñay<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice><lb break="no" n="10"/>jñāpayitavyāḥ<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied><space type="binding-hole"/><!--
I retain Mirashi's reading of ṣadviśaka in l7. He suggests the emendation ṣaḍviṁśati (and likewise for ṣadviṣati in IN00160:8). I believe we could very well read ṣaḍ both here and in IN00160; I don't expect ḍ to look conspicuously different from d in this script; compare ṣoḍaśy (read as such by Mirashi) in IN00158:1.
--><!--
In l8 Mirashi prints a double daṇḍa after vastavyāya and a single one after taittirīyāya. The former seems to be two dots one below the other; the latter a single dot. I transcribe both as single daṇḍas.
--></p>
        <p>viditam astu vaḥ yathehāsmābhir ātmano dharmmāyu<supplied reason="omitted">r</supplied>-bbala vijayaiśvaryya-
<lb n="11"/>v<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>i</corr>
          </choice>vr̥ddhaye<surplus>|</surplus> ihāmutra-hitārttham ātmānugrahāya<surplus>|</surplus> vaijayike dharmma-sthāne Apūrvva-dat<supplied reason="omitted">t</supplied>yā
<lb n="12"/>Udaka-pūrvvam atisr̥ṣṭaḥ|<g type="closer"/><!--
I follow Mirashi in reading āyu in l10, but there does seem to be something above bba so the originally inscribed text may actually have been rbba.
--><!--
The first punctuation mark in l11 is unrecognisable in the rubbing; it may be a single dot or short dash, or it may not be there at all. The second punctuation mark is a double dot (like a colon); Mirashi transcribes it as a double daṇḍa.
--><!--
In dharmma in l11, Mirashi prints rma in CII5; he correctly has rmma in EI24.
--><!--
The closing glyph in l12 is unclear in the rubbing; it seems to consist of two concentric circles surrounded by dots. Before it, there seems to be a short horizontal dash between the dots of the visarga, then possibly another dot or dash. After the circle, there are two or three very short verticals at centreline height, then a long horizontal dash at the same height.
--></p>
